.TH NET-SHOW 1 "2026-04-29" "net-mgr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
net-show \- list WiFi access points and look up which AP saw a given IP
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B net-show
.RB [ \-\-no\-scan ]
.br
.B net-show
.BI \-find= IP
.RB [ \-\-no\-scan ]
.br
.B net-show
.RB [ \-\-listen
.IR HOST:PORT ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-show
lists access points known to net-mgr along with their SSIDs, board models, and
last-seen times. With
.BI \-find= IP
it locates which AP and lease history the given address came from \(em useful
for tracking down where a device joined the network.
.PP
By default
.B net-show
fires a scan-ap trigger to refresh AP data before printing. Pass
.B \-\-no\-scan
to skip the refresh and print whatever's already in the database.
.PP
This tool replaces the legacy
.IR /usr/local/bin/show-ap .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-find=\fIIP\fR
Show which AP saw
.IR IP ,
including the lease record (if any) and recent association history.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-scan
Skip the
.B TRIGGER scan-ap
step. Faster; uses the DB as-is.
.TP
\fB\-\-listen\fR \fIHOST:PORT\fR
Override the manager address.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
List all APs:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-show
.fi
.RE
.PP
Find the AP that gave 192.168.15.42 its lease:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-show -find=192.168.15.42
.fi
.RE
.PP
Quick listing, no fresh poll:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-show --no-scan
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR net-poll-ap (1),
.BR net-roam (1),
.BR net-report (1),
.BR net-mgr (7)
